.TH HSH 1 "April 2026" "1.1" "Simple Shell Manual"

.SH NAME
hsh \- simple UNIX command line interpreter

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B hsh

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B hsh
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter written in C for educational purposes.
It reads commands from standard input, parses them, resolves executable paths using the
.B PATH
environment variable, creates child processes, and executes programs using system calls.

The shell behaves similarly to
.BR sh (1)
in basic functionality, supporting both interactive and non-interactive modes.
It repeatedly displays a prompt, reads user input, executes commands, and waits for completion.

Advanced shell features such as pipes, redirections, quoting, command chaining,
background execution, and wildcards are not supported.

.SH EXECUTION FLOW
The shell follows a standard command processing cycle:

.PP
read -> parse -> resolve -> fork -> execve -> wait -> repeat

.PP
More specifically:
.TP
.B 1.
User input is read using getline()
.TP
.B 2.
Command is parsed into arguments
.TP
.B 3.
Executable is resolved via PATH lookup
.TP
.B 4.
A child process is created using fork()
.TP
.B 5.
The command is executed using execve() in the child process
.TP
.B 6.
Parent process waits for completion using wait()
.TP
.B 7.
The prompt is displayed again

.SH FEATURES
- Interactive prompt display
- Execution of commands with arguments
- PATH-based executable resolution
- Support for end-of-file (Ctrl+D)
- Error handling for unknown commands
- Built-in command support

.SH BUILT-IN COMMANDS
The following built-in commands are supported:

.TP
.B exit
Exit the shell and terminate the program.

.TP
.B env
Print the current environment variables.

.SH USAGE

Interactive mode:
.PP
.RS
$ ./hsh
.br
($) ls
.br
($) env
.br
($) exit
.RE

Non-interactive mode:
.PP
.RS
echo "/bin/ls" | ./hsh
.br
cat file.txt | ./hsh
.RE

.SH ENVIRONMENT
The shell relies on environment variables, especially:

.TP
.B PATH
Used to locate executable programs.

.SH EXIT STATUS
Returns 0 on success and non-zero on error.

.SH ERRORS
If a command is not found, the shell prints:

.PP
.RS
./hsh: 1: command not found
.RE

The program name corresponds to argv[0].

.SH LIMITATIONS
This shell does not support:
.PP
pipes, redirections, command chaining, background execution,
quoting, wildcards, or scripting features.

.SH REQUIREMENTS
- Ubuntu 20.04 LTS
- gcc -Wall -Werror -Wextra -pedantic -std=gnu89
- Betty coding style
- No memory leaks allowed
- Maximum 5 functions per file

